It took me a good hour to figure out why the following fragment of code didn't work:

final IProcess proc = ac.createProcess();				
proc.setExecutable("java.exe");
proc.setParameter("-classpath %CLASSPATH%;D:\\TPTP4.2\\TPTP-4.2.0-200604101029\\eclipse\\workspaces\\runtime-EclipseApplication\\JavaProject  HelloWorld");

IConsole console = proc.getConsole();
IDataProcessor dp = new ClientDataProcessor();
console.setDataProcessor(dp);

proc.launch();
System.out.println("Process ID ::=>>"+ proc.getProcessId());

I was consistently getting the following exception:


org.eclipse.tptp.platform.execution.exceptions.NoSuchApplicationException: Error: The process launch command execution failed. There is no such application. The error code and error info - 6003 and "Unable to Start Process : Directory Not Found"
	at org.eclipse.tptp.platform.execution.client.core.internal.ProcessImpl.launchAC(ProcessImpl.java:696)
	at org.eclipse.tptp.platform.execution.client.core.internal.ProcessImpl.launch(ProcessImpl.java:119)
	at org.eclipse.tptp.platform.execution.samples.TPTPProcess.main(TPTPProcess.java:76)



It turns out that I needed to set the location before doing the launch:
proc.setLocation(".");

We shouldn't require clients to set a location before a launch.  It should by default be set to "."
